<h1>Problem 1866 - 2024 Balkan MO, P3 of 4, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(a\) and \(b\) be distinct positive integers such that \(3^a + 2\) is divisible by \(3^b + 2\). Prove that \(a > b^2\).</p>
<h2>Thinking</h2>
<div class= skib>
<p>We have
\[3^b \equiv -2 \pmod{3^b + 2}\]
\[3^a \equiv -2 \pmod{3^b + 2}\]
So \(a \ge b + o\) where \(o\) is the order of \(3\) modulo \(3^b + 2\). So we want to show the non-existence of \(o \le b^2 - b\) such that
\[3^o \equiv 1 \pmod{3^b+2}\]
\[-2 \cdot 3^{o - b} \equiv 1 \pmod{3^b + 2}\]
Now let \(x\) be the largest number such that \(o - xb \ge 0\). We want to show that \(x > b - 1\).
\[(-2)^x \cdot 3^{o - xb} \equiv 1 \pmod{3^b + 2} \implies^{\diamondsuit} (-2)^{x+1} \cdot 3^{o - xb} \equiv 3^b \pmod{3^b + 2}^\diamondsuit \implies (-2)^{x+1} \equiv 3^{b(x+1) - o} \pmod{3^b + 2}\]
Note that since \(0 \le o - xb < b\), we know \(0 < (x + 1)b - o \le b\). Assume FTSOC \(x \le b - 1\). When \((x+1)b - o = b\), then the only value of \(x\) that works for the power of \(2\) is \(0\), a contradiction. Otherwise, we have \(3^{\le b - 1} - (-2)^{\le b} \equiv 0 \pmod{3^b + 2}\). However, this cannot be equal to \(0\) since one is a power of \(3\) and the other is a power of \(2\), and this cannot be equal to a positive multiple of \(3^b + 2\) since
\[3^{b - 1} + 2^b \le 3^b + 2\]
So \(x > b - 1\) must hold, implying \(o > b^2 - b\), implying \(a > b^2\), and we are done. 
</div>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>Nice Euclidean algorithm spotted. Honestly the \(\diamondsuit\) part is the main part of the problem. You have two things multiplied together which is genuinely useless because it doesn't imply anything by size - but you have a way to convert it to them being on opposite sides of the congruence. Grab that opportunity and size.</p>
<p>\(1\)s in your congruences may be neat but they don't mean anything if you're not getting anything from them. Don't be afraid of losing \(1\)s.</p>
